image.altText: Snowtown accomplice Mark Ray Haydon.

props.synopsis: South Australia's Parole Board will meet to consider an application by "bodies-in-the-barrels" accomplice Mark Ray Haydon for release into the community. It’s the culmination of an application which has been under consideration since 2021.

title.children: A man convicted of helping the Snowtown murderers is seeking early release on parole. Here's what's next

image.altText: People walk past roadside stalls selling coca cola and sprite, on a dirt road

props.synopsis: Papua New Guinea is reeling from a bloody massacre in the Highlands province of Enga, and the bloodshed suggests an armoury of automatic weapons funnelled through powerful community leaders is fuelling the violence.

title.children: PNG police say tribesmen who killed dozens in Enga massacre had M16s, AR15s and self-loading rifles

image.altText: Photorealistic concept art of a warship gliding through open seas.

props.synopsis: Labor reveals the cost of the massive Hunter-class frigate project has leapt from $45 billion to almost $65 billion, as it prepares to trim the program while unveiling other shipbuilding plans.

title.children: $20 billion funding 'hole' in troubled Hunter warships, Labor claims

image.altText: an outside view of a row of houses

props.synopsis: When it comes to housing, we're witnessing a shortage of supply while demand is ramping up from a huge lift in population, fuelled by incredibly generous tax breaks. It doesn't bode well for affordability, writes Ian Verrender.

title.children: How turbocharging a tax policy from a bygone era could result in the death of affordable housing

image.altText: Tim Stannard stands in front of a lamp and picture in his loung room.

props.synopsis: Tim Stannard says he's had long COVID for four years and can no longer hold down a job. Experts say patients feel let down by the government's response to a parliamentary inquiry into long the disease, calling it a "missed opportunity".

title.children: Tim thought he had 'a little flu', but four years later he can no longer hold down a job

image.altText: two bottles of gin side by side

props.synopsis: You might not have noticed, but Australia's biggest liquor retailers are now selling vast numbers of their own private label wine, beer and pre-mixes. It's leading to concerns about a further concentration of market power.

title.children: Major supermarket chain accused of 'deceptive' labeling on homebrand Tasmanian gin

image.altText: A sign on a fence says 'asbestos'.

props.synopsis: Asbestos, it seems, is everywhere around Sydney at the moment. 7.30 went to industry insiders to find out why. The answer according to someone else who owns a similar business is a "major let-down in processes".

title.children: ACT and Queensland now testing mulch for asbestos as contamination concerns spread

image.altText: A number of illustrations of grocery items, like milk, apples, sausages, around two 'specials' signs 'half price' and '40% off'.

title.children: Specials, phantom brands, price matching: The shopping list of supermarket tactics you need to know about

image.altText: people sit in chairs in a circle.

title.children: US presents alternative UN resolution to prevent further escalation in Israel-Gaza war

image.altText: Satellite images show Rafah's tent city

props.synopsis: The city was once a "safe zone" for displaced Gazans. Now new satellite images reveal the reality of those fleeing the conflict.

title.children: Satellite images of Rafah reveal the reality of more than 1 million people fleeing conflict

image.altText: Close up of man holding uncut green gem the size of aa 50-cent piece

title.children: This whopping sapphire was unearthed in Qld. Meet the gem hunters vying to find more

image.altText: Assange, seen here looking much younger, holds up the newspaper which reads massive leak of secret fules exposes true Afghan war

title.children: Julian Assange is about to face his last fight for freedom. Here's how we got here

image.altText: A bird's eye view of unit blocks and apartments with the ocean in the background on a sunny day.

title.children: The price gap between houses and apartments is at a record high. Does it mean units are undervalued?

image.altText: The flags of China and the USA are being displayed on a smartphone, with an NVIDIA chip visible in the background.

props.synopsis: A vast technology gap that has eaten deeply into Australia's ability to determine its own path is now so vast, it has become impossible to bridge, writes Linton Besser.

image.altText: A young woman with long blonde hair and wearing a sparkly silver bodysuit blows a kiss.

image.altText: A woman and man with their arms around each other.

image.altText: A Sushi Hub store in central Sydney advertises for staff.

image.altText: A sign of a waste facility with an arrow pointing towards public trailer waste.

image.altText: A smiling woman with short hair next to a man whose face is blurred

image.altText: Image shows a five-person panel on ABC's Q+A with host Patricia Karvelas

title.children: 'I have no problems with it': Labor senator welcomes drug, alcohol testing in parliament

image.altText: A wooden cross sticks up out of green grass, against a blue sky

image.altText: Close up of Taylor Swift looking serious on stage in sparkly bodysuit

image.altText: An artist rendering of a black hole inside a mass of fiery red and orange material.

image.altText: Woman and dog wrapped in muslin cloth

image.altText: A man dressed in police uniform and holding a gun stands on a street with cars nearby.

props.synopsis: The awards which brings together the biggest names in movies, television, music and pop culture in general. Here's some of the looks we've seen so far.
